[[File:Duoplasmatron.svg|thumb|Illustration of a Duoplasmatron]]
The '''Duoplasmatron''' is an [[ion source]] in which a [[cathode]] [[Hot cathode|filament]] emits electrons into a [[vacuum chamber]].<ref name="Wolf1995">{{cite book|author=Bernhard Wolf|title=Handbook of Ion Sources|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qoQHMSBNFsAC&pg=PA47|date=31 August 1995|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|isbn=978-0-8493-2502-1|pages=47–}}</ref> A gas such as [[argon]] is introduced in very small quantities into the chamber, where it becomes [[charge (physics)|charged]] or [[ionized]] through interactions with the free electrons from the cathode, forming a [[Plasma (physics)|plasma]]. The plasma is then accelerated through a series of at least two highly charged grids, and becomes an ion beam, moving at fairly high speed from the [[aperture]] of the device.
==History== The duoplasmatron was invented by [[Manfred von Ardenne]].<ref name="Walls1990">{{cite book|author=J. M. Walls|title=Methods of Surface Analysis: Techniques and Applications|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1uszAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA27|year=1990|publisher=[[CUP Archive]]|isbn=978-0-521-38690-6|pages=27–}}</ref> Later development by [[Harold R. Kaufman]] resulted in the ''Kaufman Duoplasmatron'' which has been used for applications as diverse as [[semiconductor]] manufacture, and [[spacecraft]] [[Spacecraft propulsion|propulsion]].{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}
