'''Grane oil pipeline''' ({{lang-no|Grane oljerørledning}}) is a pipeline system in western [[Norway]]. It is {{convert|220|km}} long and runs from [[Grane oil field]] to [[Sture terminal]], located {{convert|65|km}} north of [[Bergen]], Norway. The pipeline operations commenced with start of production in the Grane oil field.<ref name=Scandoil> {{cite news | url= http://www.scandoil.com/moxie-bm2/field/norway/pipeline_land_facilites/grane-oil-pipeline.shtml | title= Grane Oil Pipeline | publisher= Scandinavian Oil and Gas Magazine | date=2007-07-29 | accessdate=2009-12-07 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref>
==Technical features== The pipeline diameter is {{convert|29|in|mm}}. Capacity of Grane oil pipeline is {{convert|34000|m3/d}} of oil.<ref>[http://www.eia.doe.gov/cabs/Norway/Oil.html Energy Information Administration. ''Official energy Statistics from the U.S. Government]</ref> The greatest sea depth pipeline passes through is {{convert|355|m}} - through the [[Norwegian Trench]]. Over 110,000&nbsp;tonnes of rock and gravel was used on the seabed to establish the correct foundation for the pipeline.<ref> {{cite press release | url= http://www.hydro.com/en/Press-room/News/Archive/2002/August/16189/ | title= Grane oil pipeline in place | publisher= [[Norsk Hydro]] | date=2002-08-21 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090108110545/http://www.hydro.com/en/Press-room/News/Archive/2002/August/16189/ | archivedate = 2009-01-08 | accessdate=2009-12-07 }}</ref> The estimated lifetime of the pipeline is expected to be 30&nbsp;years.<ref name=Scandoil/>
==Ownership== The Grane pipeline is operated by [[Statoil]] and includes other partners. {| class=wikitable !Company !Share |- |[[Petoro|Petoro AS]] |48.60% |- |[[ExxonMobil|ExxonMobil Exploration and Production Norway AS]] |25.60% |- |Statoil |24.40% |- |[[ConocoPhillips|Norske Conoco AS]] |2.4% |- |} Total investment at start-up was nearly 1.6 billion [[Norwegian krone|NOK]]'s.<ref name=Scandoil/>
